HEADWORD: Smoulder
<hw>Smoul"der</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Smoldered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or <conjf>Smouldered</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Smoldering</conjf> or
<conjf>Smouldering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>smolderen</ets>;
cf. Prov. G. <ets>sm⟦oum⟧len</ets>, <ets>smelen</ets>, D.
<ets>smeulen</ets>. Cf. <er>Smell</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To burn
and smoke without flame; to waste away by a slow and supressed
combustion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>smoldering</qex> dust did round about him smoke.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exist in a state of suppressed or smothered
activity; to burn inwardly; <as>as, a <ex>smoldering</ex>
feud</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

